                            HOW TO MAKE GOOD QUESTS

     _________________________________________________________________
   
   
Perhaps the most important point about designing a quest is to think as
a player and not a designer. 
   
A PLAYER SHOULD NOT TO BE KILLED WITHOUT WARNING
At its most basic level, this means that a room with three exits, two
leading to instant death and the third to treasure,  must have a include
a clearly worded warning in the long description.  If death traps are 
thematic to the whole quest, there should be a warning in the quest hint.

A PLAYER SHOULD NOT TO BE TRAPPED WITHOUT WARNING 
If the ground beneath your feet is likely to give way and drop you into a
pit, a warning sign stating unstable ground should be in the preceding room.
Having the door slam shut behind you, unexpectedly is quite frustrating. 
Players should not have to quit out, losing equipment and quest items, 
because they went east instead of west, unless there is a hint that says 
the road to the east looks dangerous.
  
MAKE THE WARNINGS CLEAR
A warning can be hidden hidden without being obscure. It isn't necessary to
state outright:  If you go east you will fall into a trap, but saying the road
to the east is made of a different kind of dirt is not a warning that 
it is unstable.

EVERYTHING REQUIRED TO SOLVE THE QUEST SHOULD BE IN THE QUEST AREA
A player shouldn't have to bring some bit of information from another mud
or from 'mud lore'into the area.  Needing a bag to dive underwater is okay
but there should be some clue that a bag lets you dive underwater, somewhere
in the area.  If the area is going to require torches, then there should be
torches provided or the quest hint should suggest them.


THE PLAYER SHOULD BE ABLE TO SOLVE THE QUEST THE FIRST TIME THROUGH
For example if there is something which needs cooking for the right length 
of time. The only way to find out the right time is by trial and error. But 
you only get one try per reset.  This is unfair.  In principal a good 
player should be able to solve the entire quest without doing anything illogical.
Players shouldn't have to wait out resets because they didn't "guess"
the right answer.
   
THE PLAYER SHOULD BE ABLE TO FINISH WITHOUT KNOWLEDGE OF FUTURE EVENTS
For example, the quest starts near a shop. You have one coin and can buy
a lamp, a magic carpet or a periscope. Five minutes later you are
transported away without warning to a submarine, whereupon you need a
periscope. If you bought the carpet, bad luck.
   

THE PLAYER SHOULD NOT TO NEED TO DO UNLIKELY THINGS
For example if every quest in the game either returns an object or a 
search fail message on the first search attempt, your quest should not 
make a player search a number of times in the same spot, without giving 
them the hint to continue searching.  
   
  
MAKE FORGIVING SYNTAX
If you have a loose brick in the wall and the player has to pull it out   
in order to open a hidden door forgive them from getting only half the 
solution and give them a little prod to let them know they are on the 
right track.  This is frustrating:
look at wall
   It is made of bricks
look at bricks
   One of them is loose
look at brick
   Which brick do you want to look at?
look at loose brick
   It looks loose.
get brick
   You can't take that
push brick
   What?
pull brick
   What?
move brick
   What?
Seeing What? over and over is extremely frustrating.  If you think the 
player is likely to attempt the syntax them put the response in:
push brick
   It doesn't budge.
move brick
   It doesn't budge.
pull brick
   You pull gently on the brick moving it a little.
pull brick hard
   You tug the brick right out of the wall.  The wall slides open 
   revealing a hidden exit.
   
  
   
DON'T GIVE TOO MANY RED HERRINGS
A red herring is something that looks like a clue, but is not related to the
quest.  They help add to the theme, and to make the quest area fuller but
at some point in the quest it should become obvious that an item that the 
player is carrying around because it seemed important, isn't.   


A PLAYER SHOULD NOT TO NEED TO BE AMERICAN TO UNDERSTAND HINTS
Don't require "Americanized" words to be used to solve the quest.  Accept 
both the English and the American spelling of important responses.  Not 
all players are Americans.  Not all players have English as their first 
language.  Making a quest dependant on obscure American syntax, American 
expressions or ideals, or totally dependant on American spellings makes 
it frustrating for non-American players.

   
SET THE PLOT AND STICK TO IT
It is a good idea to lay out clear plan on paper first.  You will have 
to write out a description of how your quest works from start to finish 
when you submit it anyway.  The dreaded flow chart is a useful tool when 
laying out your quest plan.  Once you have chosen the plot and the theme.  
You can fill in the areas around it.  Make sure that the quest doesn't 
deviate from the plot.  If a player is questing to stop a war between the 
elves and the vikings in Hyper they shouldn't find themselves battling 
mermaids in the ocean.

SET THE ATMOSPHERE
The quest hint should include a general idea of what a player is expected 
to do and a good clue as to where to go to get the first hint.  The first 
hint should set the atmosphere and explain the plot.  Don't make a player sit
through a 10 minute story to hear the plot.  Do give a good overview and
an idea of where to go next.

GIVE ADEQUATE CLUES
Wandering around finding bits and pieces is part of every quest.  Make sure 
hint should set the plot and the atmosphere.  Don't make a player sit
together.  This is one of the difficult parts of coding a quest.  Since you 
are the coder, you know the ending.  Don't assume that every player will do 
things exactly the same as you do.

GIVE MILESTONES
Even if a quest isn't linear, there should be some indication that the half 
way mark has been passed.  There are few things more frustrating to a
quester than to find that they gave up after 8 hours of questing yesterday 
when they only needed one more piece to finish.

